Machine learning analysis of RNA-seq data

Author

Prof. Francesca Finotello

Introduction

Machine learning is a branch of AI that learns patterns from data to make predictions or decisions. In supervised learning, models are trained on labeled data to map inputs to outputs, performing regression (predicting quantitative values) or classification (predicting categories). In unsupervised learning, models identify patterns in unlabeled data, for example through clustering, which groups similar data points, or dimensionality reduction techniques such as principal component analysis (PCA), which reduce data dimensionality while preserving as much information content as possible.

In this set of exercises, we will apply a selection of machine learning techniques to investigate cancer RNA-seq data. We will start from a dataset from the Cancer Cell Line Encyclopedia (CCLE), which contains RNA-seq data summarized in a gene transcripts per million (TPM) matrix across more than 100 cancer cell lines from different tumor types.

Exercises

Data access and initialization

The CCLE matrix of TPM and the sample/cell line annotations can be downloaded in the form or an R file (“CCLE_data.rda”) from the course OpenOLAT entry at this link. Note: you need to be logged in to access the file.

Once saved in the working directory, the object can be loaded into RStudio using the following command; In case the file is not located working directory, make sure to specify the correct file path.

load("CCLE_data.rda", verbose = TRUE)

  tpm
  tissue

Before we begin the analysis, let’s set the seed of the random number generator as indicated below to ensure reproducible plots and results:

set.seed(1234)

Let’s also convert tpm to log-scale to reduce data skeweness (1 is added to avoid having log(0) which is not defined):

log_tpm <- log(tpm + 1)

Exercise 1

In this exercise we will perform PCA of this dataset for 2D-visualization. PCA is performed with the prcomp, which expects observations on the rows of the input data, and variables on columns. As our dataset log_tpm has instead observations (i.e., samples/cell lines_ on the columns, and variables (i.e., genes) on the rows, we need to first transpose it using the t function:

pca_result <- prcomp(t(log_tpm))

The results are saved in a variable called pca_result, which is a list (also) containing:

  • pca_result$x: sample coordinates in principal component space;
  • pca_result$rotation: loadings, i.e. contribution of each gene to each principal component (PC);
  • pca_result$sdev: standard deviations of the PC.

We can now extract the sample coordinates along the first PC (pc1) and second PC (pc2):

pc1 <- pca_result$x[, 1]
pc2 <- pca_result$x[, 2]

We can now plot the samples in PC space (PC2 vs. PC1), using dots (pch = 19) to represent the samples:

plot(
  pc1, pc2,
  pch = 19
)

From the standard deviation, we can calculate the variance explained by the first two PC (rounded to 1 digit) and add this information to the plot axes; the paste0 function is used to paste together strings of text (between quotes) and the values stored in variables like var1 and var2:

var1 <- round(pca_result$sdev[1]^2 / 100, 1)
var2 <- round(pca_result$sdev[2]^2 / 100, 1)
plot(
  pc1, pc2,
  pch = 19,
  xlab = paste0("PC1 (", var1, "%)"),
  ylab = paste0("PC2 (", var2, "%)")
)

By definig a palette based on three colors, we can color the points according to their tissue of origin:

cols <- c("#7570b3", "#d95f02", "#1b9e77")
plot(
  pc1, pc2,
  pch = 19,
  xlab = paste0("PC1 (", var1, "%)"),
  ylab = paste0("PC2 (", var2, "%)"),
  col = cols[factor(tissue)]
)

To be able to interpret the results, we add a legend:

plot(
  pc1, pc2,
  pch = 19,
  xlab = paste0("PC1 (", var1, "%)"),
  ylab = paste0("PC2 (", var2, "%)"),
  col = cols[factor(tissue)]
)
legend(
  "bottomleft",
  legend = levels(factor(tissue)),
  col = cols,
  pch = 19,
  bty = "n"
)

❓ Question: Which is the cancer type showing the most marked separation from the other two?

Click to see the answer

Answer:

The biggest difference in this dataset is between skin and the other two tissues (breast/pancreas), as they are separated by the widest gap along the PC1 axis.

Click to see the answer

Answer:

Breast and pancreas cancer cell lines show some overlap in PC space, which suggests that they may share certain molecular molecular programs, which are distinct instead from those found in the skin.

Click to see the answer

Answer:

The wide spread of the breast cancer samples indicates a larger heterogeneity, which could suggest the presence of different molecular subtypes.

Exercise 2

We can extract the loadings of PC1 and PC2:

load1 <- pca_result$rotation[,1]
load2 <- pca_result$rotation[,2]

We can sort them by absolute value, so that features with the strongest positive or negative association with PC1 or PC2 appear first.

load1 <- load1[order(abs(load1), decreasing = TRUE)]
load2 <- load2[order(abs(load2), decreasing = TRUE)]

Now, with head, we can inspect the first three genes associated with PC1 and their loadings, ans use Gene Cards to under=stand their biological role:

Exercise 3

The aim of this exercise it to perform hierarchical clustering of the cell lines and visualize the results via a dendrogram. In order to make the final gaphs legible, we will decrease the sample size of this dataset by randomly selecting 30 cell lines with the sample function. We will save this reduced dataset and the associated tissue annotations in the log_tpm_small and tissue_small objects, respectively, and we can check with table how many cell lines per cancer type we have in the reduced dataset.

sel <- sample(30)
log_tpm_small <- log_tpm[,sel]
tissue_small <- tissue[sel]
table(tissue_small)
tissue_small
  BREAST PANCREAS     SKIN 
      13        6       11

To proceed with clustering analysis, we need to first compute distances between samples/cell lines using the dist function. If no specific options are provided to this function, Euclidean distance is used as the default distance metrics, as in the command below. To compute distances between samples (rather than genes), we need to first transpose the input data with the t function.

dist_samples <- dist(t(log_tpm_small))

Based on the distances saved in dist_samples, we can now perform hierarchical clustering using the hclust function, using single linkage, and save the results in an object called hc_samples_sin. By calling the plot function on this object, a dendrogram representing the clustering results is plotted.

hc_samples_sin <- hclust(dist_samples, method = "single")
plot(hc_samples_sin, 
     xlab = "", 
     sub = "", 
     cex = 0.8,
     main = "Single Linkage")

In omics data analysis, Ward’s linkage (not discussed in class) is frequently used because it often produces more compact and interpretable clusters. Let’s apply this method and examine the resulting dendrogram.

hc_samples_war <- hclust(dist_samples, method = "ward.D2")
plot(hc_samples_war, 
     xlab = "", 
     sub = "", 
     cex = 0.8,
     main = "Ward D2 Linkage")

❓ Question: Compare the dendrograms obtained using the two linkage methods: what differences do you observe?

Exercise 4

The aim of this exercise is to perform binary classification of our RNA-seq datasets, aiming to identify skin cancer cell lines by distuinguishing them from breast cancer cell lines. To this end, we will first select from the original datasets only the samples corresponding to skin or breast cancer cell lines.

sel <- which(tissue %in% c("BREAST", "SKIN"))
log_tpm_SK <- log_tpm[,sel]
tissue_SK <- factor(tissue[sel])

To identify skin cacer cell lines, we decide to first test a score based on the MKI67 gene, encoding the Ki-67 marker of proliferation, which is known to be upregulated in cancer cells. We can use GeneCards to see that the Ensembl identifier for the MKI67 is ENSG00000148773. We can now define a score based on the log-scaled expression in TPM of this gene:

mki67_score <- as.numeric(log_tpm_SK["ENSG00000148773",])

As we know the real class of every cell line (tissue_SK), we can perform Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve (ROC) analysis, testing the classification performance of this score at different cut-offs. For this analysis, we need to load the pROC R package.

library(pROC)

Once the package is loaded, we can use its roc function to perform ROC analysis, and compute the area under the curve (AUC) of this score.

mki67_roc <- roc(tissue_SK, mki67_score)
Setting levels: control = BREAST, case = SKIN
Setting direction: controls > cases
mki67_auc <- auc(mki67_roc)
print(paste0("AUC=", round(mki67_auc, 3)))
[1] "AUC=0.553"

The results of the analysis saved in mki67_roc can be visualized with the plot function.

plot(
  mki67_roc,
  col = "#7570b3",
  lwd = 2,
  main = paste0("MKI67 (AUC=", round(mki67_auc, 3), ")")
)

❓ Question: How do you interpret these results?

Click to see the answer

Answer:

The AUC for this predictor is 0.553, only slightly above 0.5, which corresponds to random guessing. The ROC curve closely follows the diagonal, consistent with a near-random classifier. Overall, these results indicate that the MKI67 score is a suboptimal predictor for distinguishing skin cancer cell lines from breast cancer cell lines, likely due to expression of this marker in both tumor types.

We can try another classifier, which is focused on a gene that is characterized by a more specific expression in skin cancer. MART-1/melan-A is a protein antigen that is found on the surface of melanocytes, and is encoded by the MLANA gene.

❓ Question: How can we define a score based on MLANA gene expression and evaluate its classification performance through ROC analysis?

Click to see the answer

Answer:

mlana_score <- as.numeric(log_tpm_SK["ENSG00000120215",])
mlana_roc <- roc(tissue_SK, mlana_score)
Setting levels: control = BREAST, case = SKIN
Setting direction: controls < cases
mlana_auc <- auc(mlana_roc)
print(paste0("AUC=", round(mlana_auc, 3)))
[1] "AUC=0.906"
plot(
  mlana_roc,
  col = "#d95f02",
  lwd = 2,
  main = paste0("MLANA (AUC=", round(mlana_auc, 3), ")")
)

We can also visualize the results from both predictors/scores in the same AUC plot.

plot(mki67_roc, 
     col = "#7570b3", 
     lwd = 2, 
     main = "Skin/breast cancer classification")

lines(mlana_roc, 
      col = "#d95f02", 
      lwd = 2)

legend("bottomright", 
       legend = c(paste0("MKI67 (AUC=", round(mki67_auc, 3), ")"),
                paste0("MLANA (AUC=", round(mlana_auc, 3), ")")),
       col = c("#7570b3","#d95f02"), 
       lwd = 2)

❓ Question: How does the MLANA score perform compared to the MKI67 score in the classification of skin versus breast cancer cell lines, based on ROC analysis

Click to see the answer

Answer:

The AUC of 0.906 indicates that MLANA is an extremely strong predictor in this task and dataset. Instead, MKI67 provides provide quasi-random classification, as reflected by its much lower AUC (0.553)

Exercise X

This exercise focuses on the analysis of an RNA-seq dataset from (Mariathasan et al. 2018)[https://www.nature.com/articles/nature25501]. In this study, the authors performed RNA-seq on tumor samples collected pre-treatment from patients with bladder cancer who received cancer immunotherapy. The matrix of gene TPM and information on therapeutic response can be downloaded in the form or an R file (“Mariathasan_data.rdata”) from the course OpenOLAT entry at this link. Note: you need to be logged in to access the file.

By loading the file in R, we can see that it includes:

  • A data.frame, called tpm, with the TPM across 31,087 genes and 192 samples. Gene symbols are used as row names.
  • A vector, called response, containing threapeutic information for all the patients in this cohort indicating whether they showed response to immunotherapy (‘R’) or were instead non-responsers.

Before starting the analysis, let’s convert the TPM to logarithmic scale.

log_tpm <- log(tpm+1)

❓ Question: How many responders and non-responders? are there in this dataset? Hint: use table.

Let’s use log_tpm data to perform PCA analysis and visualize the samples in 2-dimensional PCA space.

❓ Question: How much variance is explained by PC1 and PC2?

❓ Question: Do samples separate in PCA space according to therapeutic response?

❓ Question: Which is the gene with the largest absolute PC1 loading, and the one with the largest PC2 loading? Visualize their expression level in PC space.

We want to define three scores aiming at predicting patients’ response to cancer immunotherapy:

  • PDL1: The Mariathasan study focuses on the inhibition of PD-L1. The level of PD-L1 expression has been identified as predictive of response to anti-PDL1 immunotherapy. Therefore, we can define a score based on PD-L1 expression in log-TPM. However, it is important to note that PD-L1 is not the official gene symbol and, thus, is not present in the Mariathasan dataset; the correct symbol is CD274.

  • CD8A: CD8⁺ T cells are a subpopulation of T lymphocytes that can recognize and kill tumor cells. They have been associated with favorable patient outcomes and response to cancer immunotherapy (Fridman et al. 2017). These cells are characterized by high expression of their defining markers, CD8A and CD8B. We can define a second score as the sum of the expression (log-TPM) of these two genes.

  • CYT: In a recent study (Rooney et al. 2015), the authors defined a simple score to quantify the killing capacity of cytotoxic T cells and natural killer (NK) cells. This cytolytic activity (CYT) score, which we can use as our third predictor, is based on the sum of the expression (log-TPM) of the granzyme A (GZMA) and perforin (PRF1) genes.

Let’s compute these three scores (PDL1, CD8A, CYT) and evaluate theire ability to classify patients’ response (with “R” and “NR” ground-truth labels saved in the response object) via ROC analysis with the pROC package. Compare all three predictors in a single ROC plot, which should also report their AUC.

❓ Question: Based on the plot and AUC values, which score shows the best classification performance, and which one the worst?
